SIMPLE: exaction
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Exaction
<hw>Ex*ac"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>exactio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>exaction</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of demanding with authority, and compelling to pay or
yield; compulsion to give or furnish; a levying by force; a driving to
compliance; <as>as, the <ex>exaction</ex> to tribute or of
obedience</as>; hence, extortion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Take away your <qex>exactions</qex> from my people.</q>
<rj><qau>Ezek. xlv. 9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Daily new <qex>exactions</qex> are devised.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Illegal <qex>exactions</qex> of sheriffs and officials.</q>
<rj><qau>Bancroft.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is exacted; a severe tribute; a fee,
reward, or contribution, demanded or levied with severity or
injustice.</def> <rj><au>Daniel.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Exactitude</ent>⟦br⟧
